answers.body_markdown:
Well your main issue seems not to be the calculation but a missing reference. Your code is by far not enough to tell why it is not working but I&#39;ll try:

In case the `WanderingAI` is a `MonoBehaviour` component (which seems to be the case since you are trying access `transform`

    WanderingAI w = new WanderingAI();

is an absolute **no go**! This component should be attached to a `GameObject` and either set when instantiating or has to be found on runtime dynamically.

I would guess the missing reference exception isn&#39;t thrown for `w` but rather for the line

    transform.position

in `getEnemyPos`.

We don&#39;t see where or how you Instantiate this. So just as an example you **could** (see better way below) simply hand the instantiated fireball the `Transform` reference of who fired it:

In the fireball have a field

    public Transform enemyTransform;

and then set it together with the instantiation

    public Fireball fireballPrefab;

    ...

    var fireball = Instantiate(fireballPrefab, transform.position, transform.rotation);
    fireball.enemyTransform = transform;

Your get position methods are quite redundant. `transform.position` is always public for any `GameObject` and `Componnet`(`MonoBehaviour`) reference so as soon as you have a reference to the enemy or your fireball (object or component doesn&#39;t matter) you can simply directly access e.g.

    enemy.transform.position

And just general notes: Method names in c# should start with a capital letter. And storing every single value in a local variable or class field is also quite unnecessary.

---

## However

Instead of using the responsible enemy transform **at all** you could simply store the fireballs **own start position**. Then you wouldn&#39;t have to care about the enemy anymore. Also taking the enemy&#39;s position into account in `Update` might not work correctly if the enemy moves meanwhile ;)

Since you are only moving in the `z` direction you could simply check the so far traveled distance and wouldn&#39;t even need a reference to the enemy

    // Adjust in the Inspector
    [SerializeField] private float range = 10;

    // Stores the initial position
    private Vector3 startPosition;

    private void Start()
    {
        // Store position before starting to move
        startPosition = transform.position;
    }

    private void Update ()
    {
        transform.Translate(Vector3.forward * speed * Time.deltaTime);

        // Directly compare to the initial position
        // Without having to care who fired this ball
        if(Mathf.Abs(startPosition.z - transform.position.z) &gt;= range)
        {
            Destroy(gameObject);
        }

        // Or simply
        if(Vector3.Distance(startPosition, transform.position) &gt;= range)
        {
            Destroy(gameObject);
        }
    }

---

Currently you are also only moving in **global** Z direction .. is this really what you wanted to do? Otherwise I would rather set the correct rotation when instantiating the ball and move in its local forward direction like

    transform.Translate(transform.forward * speed * Time.deltaTime);

